<td align="center">
<div class="poemtitle">A Smuggler in the Chancery</div> 
<br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('dion')">by Brian Dion</a> <br>
<br>
<br>
<table cellpadding="20" cellspacing="0"><tr><td>
<I>Westminster, 14<SUP>th</SUP> century</I><br>
<br>
&nbsp;<br>
Northumberland, still claggy on my tongue,<br>
can nae muck up my quill.  The Master rails<br>
&quot;Affairs of state must have the speech of Kings!<br>
The noble words that came by Norman sails<br>
across the channel, that’s what we use here.&quot;<br>
I heed his call and pen each day’s events:<br>
<I>deliveries</I> of <I>venison, </I>the <I>hour</I><br>
a <I>fine </I>is <I>paid</I>, <I>petitioners’ laments.<br>
<br>
</I>But when<I> </I>I can, I grant the common man<br>
his native <I>deer</I><B>, </B>his <I>calf</I><B> </B>and nae their<I> veal.</I><br>
I pen the <I>shepherd</I><B> </B><I>hounds</I> to watch his <I>sheep</I>;<br>
and in my house I’ll teach my growing son<br>
our English speech and of its stony will,<br>
then dream of Wigton wan I’ve gaan t’sleep.<br>
</td>
<td align="right"><img src="images/smugglerchancery.jpg"><br><span class="byartist">Patricia Wallace Jones</span></td>
</tr></table>
</td>
</tr>
